{
  "text": "The constitutive suppression of osteoblast function in Cgt \u00ff/\u00ff mice might be due to increased sympathetic tone [CITATION_1] or, alternatively, a reduction in putative neurally transmitted trophic signals. Osteoblasts have been reported to express receptors for several neuropeptides, suggesting that they could indeed integrate multiple neuronal signals [CITATION_2] . We have measured NE turnover in cardiac tissues of Cgt littermates and found a longer halflife in Cgt \u00ff/\u00ff hearts, indicating reduced peripheral sympathetic activity in the null mice ( Figure S4 [CITATION_3] , indicating that the earliest committed lymphoid progenitor cell may require osteoblasts for survival, proliferation, or differentiation. A close relationship between CLP and the stem cell niche is further suggested by the expression of the Notch-1 ligand, Jagged-1, in the osteoblastic niche and the fact that Notch-1 can promote both stem cell self-renewal and differentiation toward the lymphoid lineage [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . More differentiated B cell precursors (B220+flk2+), distant from the endosteum, are closely associated with CXCL12-expressing stromal cells, which do not express the Notch-1 ligands Jagged-1 or Delta-like-1 [CITATION_7] . Further studies are thus needed to determine whether the nervous system influences homeostatic migration of stem cells among cellular niches in the BM. In summary, we show here that the sympathetic nervous system regulates the egress of stem and progenitor cells from their niche. These results raise the interesting possibility that alterations in the sympathetic tone may explain the conspicuous variability in mobilization efficiencies among normal donors [CITATION_8] . Modulation of the sympathetic outflow to the stem cell niche represents a novel strategy to increase the efficiency of HSPC harvests for stem cell-based therapeutics.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "11171580",
